**dbM:**

dBm (decibel-milliwatts) is a unit of power level expressed in decibels (dB) relative to one milliwatt (mW). It is commonly used in radio, microwave, and fiber-optical communication to measure the power of system transmissions.

To measure dBm, you use the following formula:

Power (dBm)=10⋅log10​(1 mWPower (mW)​)

Here’s a step-by-step process:

Measure the power in milliwatts (mW).

Apply the formula: Take the logarithm (base 10) of the power in milliwatts divided by 1 milliwatt.

Multiply by 10 to convert the logarithmic value to decibels.

For example, if you have a power level of 10 mW, the calculation would be:

Power (dBm)=10⋅log10​(1 mW10 mW​)=10⋅log10​(10)=10⋅1=10 dBm

In dBm, a higher value indicates greater power. Therefore, -4 dBm is greater than -40 dBm.

To put it in perspective, dBm values are on a logarithmic scale, so each 10 dB decrease represents a tenfold decrease in power. Thus, -4 dBm represents a higher power level than -40 dBm.

Gemini:

The unit dBm (decibel-milliwatts) is used to express the power level of a signal in decibels relative to one milliwatt. It's a logarithmic scale, meaning each 10 dBm increase represents a tenfold increase in power.

Here's a breakdown of its uses:

- Wireless Communications: dBm is commonly used to measure signal strength in Wi-Fi, cellular, and other radio frequency systems. A higher dBm value indicates a stronger signal.
- Fiber Optics: dBm is used to express the optical power levels in fiber optic communication systems.
- Audio Engineering: dBm can be used to measure audio signal levels, although other units like dBu are more common in this field.

Key Points:

- 0 dBm equals 1 milliwatt.
- dBm is an absolute measurement of power, unlike dB (decibel), which is a relative measurement.
- dBm values are typically expressed in negative numbers for weaker signals (e.g., -70 dBm) and positive numbers for stronger signals (e.g., 30 dBm).

Understanding dBm is crucial for anyone working with wireless communication systems, as it helps in assessing signal strength, troubleshooting connectivity issues, and designing efficient networks.

Conclusion reg the dbM:

Higher the dbm value --> Higher the Power consumption

Lower the value ---> Less consumption of Power

Indoor/Outdoor Manual Mode:

1. Login to the Nomadia Protect Mobile Application > Ensure that the Home screen header becomes red color / Notification/ Widget status as mentioned in the Image (Ref:Undefined Status)
2. Ensure that you are not in the range of the Beacons > Click on the Unsafe Location Widget on the Mobile
3. Approach the Closest Beacon> Wait for some time(10 to 15 sec)> Check the status
4. Ensure that you are away from the Beacons Range for sometime > Ensure that the status becomes Outdoor  > Click on the Widget Outdoor
5. Ensure that you are  in Beacons Range > Wait for some time(10-15 sec)
6. In ECW (Nomadia-Protect Backoffice) > Disable the Indoor/Outdoor Feature > Open Nomadia Protect Mobile

Indoor/Outdoor Automatic Mode:

1. Open the Nomadia Protect Mobile> Ensure that the Home screen header becomes red color / Notification/ Widget status as mentioned in the Image (Ref:Undefined Status)
2. Ensure that you are not in the range of the Beacons > Click on the Unsafe Location Widget on the Mobile
3. Approach the Closest Beacon which is not configured as Indoor> Wait for some time(10 to 15 sec)> Check the status
4. Click on the Outdoor Widget > Ensure that the Status changed to Indoor
5. Switch the status to Outdoor by moving beyond the Beacon’s range.
6. Approach the Closest Beacon which is configured as Indoor> Wait for some time(10 to 15 sec)> Check the status
7. In ECW (Nomadia-Protect Backoffice) > Disable the Indoor/Outdoor Feature > Open Nomadia Protect Mobile

8. The widget status to be Unsafe , notification should display undefined Indoor/Outdoor status

Indoor/Outdoor in Semi-Automatic Mode:

1. Open the Nomadia Protect Mobile> Ensure that the Home screen header becomes red color / Notification/ Widget status as mentioned in the Image (Ref:Undefined Status)
2. Ensure that you are not in the range of the Beacons > Click on the Unsafe Location Widget on the Mobile
3. Approach the Closest Beacon which is not configured as Indoor> Wait for some time(10 to 15 sec)> Check the status
4. Approach the Closest Beacon which is configured as Indoor> Wait for some time(10 to 15 sec)> Check the status
5. Ensure that the Mobile is  Beacon's Range (Any Beacon)> Click on Unsafe Widget>Ensure that the Status changed to Indoor
6. Switch the status to Outdoor by moving beyond the Beacon’s range.
7. Approach the Closest Beacon which is not configured as Indoor> Wait for some time(10 to 15 sec)> Check the status
8. Approach the Closest Beacon which is configured as Indoor> Wait for some time(10 to 15 sec)> Check the status
9. In ECW (Nomadia-Protect Backoffice) > Disable the Indoor/Outdoor Feature > Open Nomadia Protect Mobile
